{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c33dc69-0f0a-4e04-bf29-be4e39b0057d","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                          # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want to view it in [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app) without Windows tools.\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use the **diagnostic port** via a sidecar, or consider `dotnet-monitor` for always-on collection.\n- For production, prefer short durations (15–30s) to minimize overhead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5445ce09-6d1a-4c11-bf6b-4a752a865ce5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics question — I can answer from knowledge without needing tools.","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"204F:1612ED:3BFEAD:462E7E:69F00D55"},"id":"e79e8f8d-2c90-4297-838c-b04b49046144","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:29:09.567Z","parentId":"e4f41e85-26c5-4b04-bae5-00afbd58c9b0"}
